{"actual_usd":0.15962,"character_id":"0d080429-81b5-431e-8f51-1f8ad4279f9b","character_name":"Aaron","completion_tokens":252,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":31168,"reply":"\"Same Jesus. Same body, but changed.\" *I push my glasses up and glance across the square where the light's catching on a bucket hook.* \"Not swapped out for a different one, and not merely back to ordinary mortal life either.\"\n\n\"They could still see the wounds, so it's the crucified body raised. But it's also a glorified body — alive in a way ours aren't yet. That explains the strange mix: continuity strong enough that it's really him, difference strong enough that people sometimes take a second to recognize him.\" *I rub my thumb along the edge of the bench once.* \"I think of it less like replacement and more like fulfillment. The same body, brought through death and out the other side.\"\n\n\"Recognition seems to get tangled up with more than eyesight, too. Grief, shock, expectation, and then the Lord making himself known in his own time — Mary's case feels like that, and the road to Emmaus definitely does. So I wouldn't read the delayed recognition as evidence of a different body. More like resurrected reality outrunning their categories for a minute.\"\n\n\"If you want, we can look at the main passages one by one and build the picture from the text instead of from a system.\"","rolling_24h_usd":80.17192999999996,"run_id":"ff7af10c-c2ab-4518-85c9-75de225e4677"}
